Diodonrs speaks oi the races which inhahited Britain as ‘autochthonous’ without attempting any distinction. The land was untouched, he says, by foreign invasion, and neither Bacchus nor Hercules nor any ol the heroes was reported to have made an expedition against it.

Tacitus throws a greater air ol scienoe into his speculatione on this point The red hair and large limbs oi the Caledonians he thinks indicative oi a German origin, whereas the swarthy complexione of the Silures (South Wales), the prevalence among them os curly hair, and the vieinity oi Spain argue an early iberian settlement in this part oi Britain. The parts nearest to Gaul he thinks it reasonable to suppose were peopled from that country, and in support ol this conclusion he adduces the similarity that could be observed between Gauls and Britons in religion, language, and character.
